<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>tie someone down • tie someone up</xh5><p> <i>tie someone down—</i>restrict smb.’s freedom; encumber a person: I don’t want to <u>tie you down</u>, but you do have responsibilities here at home.</p><p> <i>tie someone up—</i>1. bind a person with rope, string, etc.: The thieves left the old man <u>tied up</u> in the bedroom. 2. keep a person very busy: Writing this article should not <u>tie me up</u> for more than a week or two.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>tie someone up in knots</b>—make a person very nervous or worried: Kerry <u>tied him up in knots</u> just quoting his past utterances where he contradicted himself.</p> </entry>
